04728nam a22006735i 9781477310168DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212016txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015035741  a97814773101687 a10.7560/3101442doi  a(DE-B1597)587078  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aPN1995.9.H55bV46 2016 4aPN1995.9.H55 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.43/6531 aVenkatesh, Vinodh, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNew Maricón Cinema :bOuting Latin American Film /cVinodh Venkatesh. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2016  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I: Maricón Cinema -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One. Ficheras and Jotos in Mexican Cinema: We Just Want to Be Seen -- tChapter Two. The Maricón: On Closets and Spectacular Bodies -- tChapter Three. Final Notes on a Maricón Genre -- tPart II: New Maricón Cinema -- tChapter Four. Outing Contracorriente: On Spatial Contracts and Feeling New Maricónness -- tChapter Five. Outing El último verano de la Boyita: On Masculinities and the Moment of Engagement -- tChapter Six. XX- -- tChapter Seven. Final Notes on Outing Latin America -- tPart III: Rematerializing Bodies and the Urban Space -- tIntroduction -- tChapter Eight. Plan B: Let’s Go Back to the City -- tChapter Nine. On Children and Neoliberal Structures of Feeling -- tChapter Ten. Closing Notes on a Very Open Field -- tFilms Discussed -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRecent critically and commercially acclaimed Latin American films such as XXY, Contracorriente, and Plan B create an affective and bodily connection with viewers that elicits in them an emotive and empathic relationship with queer identities. Referring to these films as New Maricón Cinema, Vinodh Venkatesh argues that they represent a distinct break from what he terms Maricón Cinema, or a cinema that deals with sex and gender difference through an ethically and visually disaffected position, exemplified in films such as Fresa y chocolate, No se lo digas a nadie, and El lugar sin límites. Covering feature films from Argentina, Chile, Cuba, Ecuador, Mexico, Peru, the United States, and Venezuela, New Maricón Cinema is the first study to contextualize and analyze recent homo-/trans-/intersexed-themed cinema in Latin America within a broader historical and aesthetic genealogy. Working with theories of affect, circulation, and orientations, Venkatesh examines key scenes in the work of auteurs such as Marco Berger, Javier Fuentes-León, and Julia Solomonoff and in films including Antes que anochezca and Y tu mamá también to show how their use of an affective poetics situates and regenerates viewers in an ethically productive cinematic space. He further demonstrates that New Maricón Cinema has encouraged the production of “gay friendly” commercial films for popular audiences, which reflects wider sociocultural changes regarding gender difference and civil rights that are occurring in Latin America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aGay men in motion pictures. 0aHomosexuality in motion pictures. 0aMasculinity in popular culturezLatin America. 0aMotion pictureszLatin America. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/31014440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477310168423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477310168/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  